<h2>What this is</h2>
<p>You will develop a <strong>habitability framework</strong> — what conditions does life require? — and apply it to three cases:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Earth</strong> — the baseline.</li>
  <li><strong>Mars</strong> — the failed-habitable case that shows how easily habitability can be lost.</li>
  <li><strong>One exoplanet of your choosing</strong> — the unknown. Eight candidates available; you pick one in Block 6.</li>
</ul>
<p>You submit a structured comparative analysis (the Report) and defend it in a peer Stakeholder Q&A where classmates play a NASA evaluation committee deciding which exoplanet warrants the next deep observation.</p>

<h2>Why three planets including a chosen exoplanet</h2>
<p>Three is enough for cross-case comparison but small enough for genuine OPVL on each. Requiring a student-chosen exoplanet creates variety — if everyone analyses TRAPPIST-1e, the Q&A is repetitive. Diverse choices make peers actually attend to each other's evidence.</p>

<h2>What you'll be scored on</h2>
<p>The Report does triple duty: it assesses unit content (habitability conditions), it exercises <a href="/foundations/opvl-framework/">OPVL</a> on planetary data + AI, and it launches systems thinking at planetary scale. The Stakeholder Q&A in Block 10 is the C-strand component of the rubric.</p>

<p>Grade weighting: Report 70% · Stakeholder Q&A 15% · Formative work (systems diagrams, OPVL practice, peer feedback) 15%.</p>

<h2>AI Documentation</h2>
<p>If you use the <a href="/ai-partners/planet-hunter/">Planet Hunter</a>, <a href="/ai-partners/systems-diagrammer/">Systems Diagrammer</a>, <a href="/ai-partners/the-source-evaluator/">Source Evaluator</a>, <a href="/ai-partners/the-skeptic/">Skeptic</a>, or any other AI tool while working on this Report, the <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation Template</a> is required. Same rules as Unit 0: every substantive AI conversation gets documented; the "one thing the AI got wrong" gate applies.</p>

